**The Last Day of Summer**

The air tasted like copper and cut grass. It was the kind of late-August afternoon that felt like a held breath, a pause between heartbeats. I was twelve, maybe thirteen, and I remember the exact weight of the sun on my shoulders as I stood at the edge of the old swimming hole, my bare feet sinking into the soft, muddy bank. The water was a perfect, impossible blue, so clear it seemed you could see the bottom of the world. My older brother, Sam, was already in, floating on his back, his dark hair slicked back like a seal’s. He was laughing about something, a sound that cut through the cicadas’ drone like a knife.

I didn’t want to go in. Not yet. I was holding something. A small, smooth stone, cool and heavy in my palm. It was the color of wet ash, and I’d found it that morning, half-buried under a pine needle carpet. I’d picked it up, thinking it was just a rock, but then I’d turned it over and seen it: a perfect, tiny spiral, etched into the stone like a fingerprint of the earth’s own design. I didn’t know what it was. A fossil? A coincidence? I just knew it was mine. A secret.

Sam saw me hesitate. “C’mon, chicken,” he teased, splashing water at me. “It’s not like it’s cold. Not really.”

I looked at the stone. I looked at the water. I looked at him. And then I did something I’d never done before. I didn’t just drop the stone into the water. I *threw* it. Hard. It arced, glinted in the sunlight, and then *plunked* far out, sending a small, perfect ring across the surface before it vanished.

Sam whooped. “There you go!” He swam towards where it went down, his strokes strong and sure. I watched the water settle, the ripples dying, the stone sinking into the depths. I felt a strange, hollow sensation in my chest, like something had been let go that I didn’t know I was holding.

That was the last day of summer. Not because the calendar said so, but because that was the last day I remember feeling like a kid. The next morning, the air was different. Sharper. The light, a little too bright. And when I went back to school, everything felt… smaller. The hallways, the lessons, the other kids. I was still me, but I wasn’t. Not really.

I didn’t find another stone like that one. I didn’t need to. The spiral had been a key, I think. Not to some hidden door, but to a realization. That the world was vast and full of things you couldn’t hold onto, not really. That even the simplest, most perfect thing—a stone, a summer day, a moment with your brother—could slip through your fingers if you weren’t careful. Or if you were.

I think about that day sometimes. Not often, but enough. I wonder if Sam remembers. I wonder if he knows that throwing that stone was the first time I truly understood that time doesn’t stop. It just keeps flowing, carrying us along, and all we can do is try to remember the ripples. [end of text]


